<br>
There is no question that slavery, and the oppression to which african-americans, native americans, and other people of color in the US have been subjected over most of the last two centures has caused lasting economic and psychological harm to members of these groups.  HOWEVER...<br>
<br>
1)  My understanding is that the oft-maligned 'Affirmative Action' programs in this country (which, being a proud old-school liberal, I do support in a limited form, but that is the topic for another debate <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) were intended to address *precisely* this issue of deprivation of economic and other opportunity that was created by slavery and racism.  I do not see that handing out cash reparations would serve any useful purpose whatsoever, even if all the decendants of actual slaves could be properly identified.  And what about all of the individuals in this country who have suffered harm due to racism, but who weren't actually slaves?<br>
<br>
2)  Some people may not regard this as a valid comparison, but in the queer community, we deal with, and talk a lot, about one of the greatest problems we face being not the abuse and oppression that is heaped on us from 'outside' communities, but the oppression and negation that we have *internalized* and impose upon ourselves, limiting our lives and our view of the world.  I've done a lot of work in 'at risk' minority communities (mostly black, in L.A. and South Dallas), and I can tell you that internalized oppression is alive and well.  Ironically, race relations are *much* better in the small Georgia town where I currently live (where there are few jobs and little opportunity) than they were in Dallas, which has had a robust economy during most of the 17 years I lived there, but *much* tension between racial groups; and black/white segregation there is nearly as severe as if someone had built a wall across the Trinity.  Probably the strangest thing I witnessed while I was there was tension between the Black and Hispanic communities as Hispanics slowly but surely became the 'majority' minority population; instead of forming coalitions, which one might expect, the groups fought each other distressingly often.  My best friend in Dallas is a Black woman my age, originally from New York; she has had a very difficult time making friends there (and almost all of her friends there are white, while her New York friends are all races) because of the entrenchment and 'cultural divide' that separates the races there.<br>
<br>
To say that slavery, and the 'Jim Crow' laws, the KKK, events like the Tulsa massacre, etc, have not left their mark upon the African-american population in the U.S. would be rediculous.  However, cash reparations, in my opinion, will do nothing to solve the problems created by our historical legacy.  Only understanding and reconciliation of these events in our history (and dealing with our ongoing racial divide) will do that, and while we should strive to make sure that equal opportunity *is* a reality for all Americans, simply throwing 'blood money' out in some bizarre gesture of 'apology' will only create more problems than it solves, in my opinion.<br>
<br>
Regards,<br>
Nydia Ywalmoriel<br>
Autonomous Collective<br>
